    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Calabash-resonated wood xylophones of Africa, introduced into Latin America where they took on various local forms. Also the modern orchestral instrument developed from Latin American models, having metal tube resonators and a four-octave compass.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xilófonos africanos de madera con resonador de calabaza, introducidos en América Latina donde tomaron diferentes formas locales. También el término se refiere al moderno instrumento orquestal desarrollado a partir de modelos Latinoamericanos, que tiene resonadores de tubos de metal y un alcance de cuatro octavas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Slaginstrumenten, in allerlei plaatselijke varianten met een  bereik van 4 octaven. De klankbodems bestaan uit kalebassen of metalen buizen onder de claviaturen; Afrika, Latijns-Amerika.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052452/Encyclopedie van muziekinstrumenten (1977)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>指以葫蘆產生共鳴的非洲木琴，後來引進拉丁美洲，在當地衍生出各種不同的種類。現代管弦樂團的瑪林巴琴，也是由拉丁美洲的瑪林巴琴發展而來，具有金屬管狀共鳴器，音域達四個八度音程。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052784/TELDAP database (2009-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Xilofones de madeira com ressonância de cabaça da África, introduzidos na América Latina, onde assumiram várias formas locais. Também o instrumento orquestral moderno desenvolvido a partir de modelos latino-americanos, possuindo ressonadores de tubo de metal e um compasso de quatro oitavas.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Portuguese</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000316/CVAA-BR</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000109633/CVAA-BR Consortium (2020-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Holzxylofon aus Afrika mit einem Kalebassenresonator, ursprünglich entstanden in Lateinamerika, wo das Instrument unterschiedliche lokale Formen hatte. Auch das moderne Orchesterinstrument entwickelte sich aus dem lateinamerikanischen Modell, mit einem Resonanzrohr aus Metall und einem Umfang über vier Oktaven.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000122134/IfM Berlin</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
    </Descriptive_Notes>
